ubstate nations. Through party manifestos, interviews with legislators, and opinion survey data, this book demonstrates that calls for constitutional change influence political debate, competition, voter choice, and the outcome of elections not only within Quebec and Scotland but also across Canada and the United Kingdom. Minority nationalist parties, the authors show, can gain support by claiming ownership of issues with widespread public agreement, such as self-determination and protecting the identity and interests of the nation. A comprehensive analysis of recent electoral politics, The National Question and Electoral Politics in Quebec and Scotland greatly enhances our understanding of the electoral impact of substate nationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aElectionszQuébec (Province) 0aElectionszQuébec (Province). 0aElectionszScotland. 0aNationalismxPolitical aspectszQuébec (Province). 0aNationalismxPolitical aspectszScotland. 0aNationalismzQuébec (Province) 0aNationalismzScotland. 0aPolitical partieszQuébec (Province) 0aPolitical partieszQuébec (Province). 0aPolitical partieszScotland. 0aVotingzQuébec (Province) 0aVotingzQuébec (Province). 0aVotingzScotland. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aHenderson, Ailsa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNadeau, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773554139?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773554139423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773554139/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles